   =20
      Private credit
   =20
 =20

Last year my friend Mary Childs  published a book about Bill Gross called T=
he Bond King: How One Man Made a Market, Built an Empire, and Lost It All.=
=C2=A0The market that Gross built was the investment-grade bond market. In =
the olden days, when Gross started out, the way bonds worked was that compa=
nies sold bonds, and insurance companies bought them and held them to matur=
ity.=C2=A0 Childs:

Bill Gross, and Pimco, started small. After struggling to find a job out of=
 business school, Gross landed at the staid old insurance company=C2=A0Paci=
fic Mutual as a securities analyst and loan officer in its fixed income dep=
artment. The business of life insurance necessitates knowing generally how =
many customers will die each year, how much an insurer will need to pay out=
, and when-ish. Usually it=E2=80=99s not for a while. So Pacific Mutual cou=
ld take its customers=E2=80=99 life insurance premia and invest the money i=
n bonds that throw off interest payments until they mature (and return the =
money) approximately when the insurer expects to need it back. It could pre=
tty safely buy a thirty-year=C2=A0bond, and earn the interest, with money f=
rom customers who most likely wouldn=E2=80=99t die for another thirty years=
. =E2=80=A6
It was not stimulating work. Gross found himself with uninteresting jobs li=
ke clipping bond coupons in Pacific Mutual=E2=80=99s vault, snipping the li=
ttle tags off the bottom of corporate certificates and mailing them in for =
interest payments. That was all a person would do with bonds at the time. F=
or the first few years, Gross couldn=E2=80=99t wait to get transferred into=
 the stocks division. But then, at the start of the 1970s, he convinced his=
 boss to let him try a radical concept: trading bonds.

Gross, and a few other innovators in the 1970s, realized that he could impr=
ove his returns by actively managing his bond portfolio: He could sell bond=
s he thought were overpriced, buy bonds he thought were underpriced, and ma=
ke higher returns with lower risk than he could by just buying bonds at iss=
ue and holding them to maturity. This was such a good idea that he ended up=
 managing money for other investors, not just for his own insurance-company=
 employer. And then other things happened in his career.
One general thing you might think about this story is that this idea, like =
so many ideas, gets less good over time. If you are the bond guy at an insu=
rance company, and all the=C2=A0other=C2=A0insurance companies just buy bon=
ds and hold them to maturity, but=C2=A0you trade bonds actively to try to m=
aximize returns, you will probably outperform your competitors. (If you can=
 find anyone to trade with you!) They are not paying attention or trying to=
 make profit-maximizing decisions, but you are; the fruit is low-hanging. B=
ut once you prove out the concept, everyone will actively trade=C2=A0bonds,=
 and not everyone can be above average at trading bonds. By the time Gross =
  retired in 2019, lots of bond portfolios were actively managed, there was=
 big money and lots of competition in the bond-management business, and Gro=
ss=E2=80=99s own recent performance wasn=E2=80=99t great.=C2=A0
If you were a hotshot innovator in the credit department of an insurance co=
mpany in the 2020s, it might occur to you to do the opposite=C2=A0of Gross.=
 You might think thoughts like these:
=09Look, I=C2=A0do=C2=A0sit on a pot of insurance money; I really=C2=A0can=
=C2=A0hold bonds to maturity. I don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0need instantaneous liqui=
dity on my bond investments. Given the choice between a liquid tradeable bo=
nd paying 6%, and an illiquid non-tradeable bond that I can=E2=80=99t sell =
for 10 years but that pays 6.5%, maybe I should take the higher interest ra=
te and just wait.=C2=A0=09There is, in general, in financial markets, an il=
liquidity premium: Bonds that can=E2=80=99t be traded tend to pay higher in=
terest rates than=C2=A0 equally good bonds that can be traded. So I probabl=
y=C2=A0can=C2=A0get an extra 0.5% for buying hard-to-trade bonds.=09When co=
mpanies issue widely tradeable bonds, there is a lot of process. They have =
to hire investment banks to find enough investors to buy the bonds; those b=
anks charge fees for their efforts. If I just=C2=A0went to companies I like=
d and asked to lend them money directly, without involving a bank, we could=
 cut out some middlemen and some fees; I would capture more of the value be=
cause the banks would get less.=C2=A0=09If I pick my own borrowers and stru=
cture my own deals, I can probably get higher returns and higher credit qua=
lity than if I just buy whatever the big banks are bringing to market each =
week, and that might be better for my performance than trying to actively t=
rade bonds in a competitive market.

Simplistically, when no one has discovered the idea of trading bonds, you c=
an get better returns by trading bonds. When everyone trades bonds, you can=
 get better returns by not trading bonds.
(As a technical point, if you were a hotshot innovator in the credit depart=
ment of an insurance company in the 2020s,=C2=A0you probably wouldn=E2=80=
=99t work at an=C2=A0insurance company; you=E2=80=99d probably work at an a=
lternative asset manager that happens to own, or run money for, an insuranc=
e company.)
At the Financial Times, Eric Platt reports on  the rise of investment-grade=
 private credit:

Alternative asset managers such as Apollo, KKR and Blackstone are increasin=
gly financing blue-chip companies, as businesses look for new sources of ca=
pital to help counteract the effects of higher interest rates and a slowing=
 economy.
The deals =E2=80=94 including two announced this month with AT&T and PayPal=
 =E2=80=94 underscore the growing reach of the private credit industry as i=
t helps companies bypass traditional banks and bond markets to raise money.=
 ...
Executives said the shift was a natural outgrowth of private credit=E2=80=
=99s fundraising spree, giving managers cash to lend. As well, most major p=
rivate equity groups have bought or invested in an insurance company in the=
 past five years, drawing in hundreds of billions of premiums to invest.
Supercharging the push has been Apollo, whose insurer Athene has amassed ne=
arly $260bn in capital =E2=80=94 roughly half of Apollo=E2=80=99s assets. .=
..
Apollo is not alone. KKR in 2021 bought a majority stake in insurer Global =
Atlantic, adding $90bn to the group=E2=80=99s assets at the time. Carlyle p=
urchased just under a fifth of reinsurer Fortitude Re from AIG in 2018 befo=
re striking a new deal last year that reduced its stake but boosted Carlyle=
=E2=80=99s assets by about $50bn. Blackstone, meanwhile, invests on behalf =
of insurers such as Corebridge through its insurance solutions division.
The insurance units are required by state regulators to invest the vast maj=
ority of their holdings in investment-grade rated debt, to safeguard policy=
holders.
But unlike traditional insurers, alternative investment managers have been =
more comfortable using financial wizardry to design private transactions th=
at can provide a few extra percentage points of return compared with tradit=
ional investment-grade corporate bonds, which yield about 5.5 per cent.

The big discovery in investment-grade credit in the 1970s was =E2=80=9Cbond=
s are liquid and fungible; let=E2=80=99s trade them to make more money.=E2=
=80=9D The big discovery in investment-grade credit in the 2020s is =E2=80=
=9Ctrading is overrated; we can make more money by doing our own structurin=
g and getting paid for illiquidity.=E2=80=9D

 =20
   =20
      Levered private credit
   =20
 =20

Platt=E2=80=99s article also contains this=C2=A0quote from Apollo:
=E2=80=9CWe made a bet on private investment grade,=E2=80=9D Marc Rowan, Ap=
ollo=E2=80=99s chief executive, told a conference this month. =E2=80=9CWe a=
re also a beneficiary of this de-banking of the world because the assets th=
at we need=E2=80=89...=E2=80=89were the kinds of things that used to go on =
to the balance sheets of banks, investment-grade private credit.=E2=80=9D
Part of the story of private credit is about (private-equity-owned) insuran=
ce companies moving from traditional insurance assets (bonds) to less-tradi=
tional insurance assets (private credit). But part of the story is about le=
nding moving from=C2=A0banks=C2=A0to (private-equity-owned) insurance compa=
nies and other direct lenders, the =E2=80=9Cde-banking of the world.=E2=80=
=9D
We have over the past few months had some occasion to talk about the philos=
ophy and social purpose of banking. =E2=80=9CBanking is a way for people co=
llectively to make long-term, risky bets without noticing them, a way to po=
ol risks so that everyone is safer and better-off,=E2=80=9D I wrote in Marc=
h. I have quoted Steve Randy Waldman=E2=80=99s 2011 post about why finance =
is complex: =E2=80=9CA banking system is a superposition of fraud and geniu=
s that interposes itself between investors and entrepreneurs.=E2=80=9D The =
point of a banking system is to transform=C2=A0risky loans=C2=A0(a bank=E2=
=80=99s assets) into=C2=A0safe bank deposits=C2=A0(a bank=E2=80=99s liabili=
ties). The bank takes risk (with your money) to make loans to businesses an=
d home buyers, but you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t take risk by depositing your mone=
y in the bank. Your money is safe, it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cmoney in the bank.=
=E2=80=9D
There is some sleight of hand here; that transformation is magical. Some of=
 it is accomplished by diversification and prudent lending and regulation a=
nd ample bank capital; some of it is accomplished by deposit insurance and =
lender-of-last-resort support for banks; some of it is just, like, residual=
 magic. Some of it is just=C2=A0belief; the banking system works because pe=
ople believe that their deposits are safe.
Earlier this month, Patrick McKenzie put it particularly well:

The fundamental purpose of bank loans is to enable measured private risk-ta=
king by leveraging a small amount of bank equity (from risk-taking investor=
s) with a larger amount of risk-adverse deposits. ...
Risk is not a=C2=A0four-letter word. Society wants restaurants, apartment b=
uildings, and crash projects to build charitable medical infrastructure. Th=
e banking system enables a higher rate of creation of these goods than woul=
d prevail in an environment where only risk capital was available to fund t=
hem. This is its main social purpose; the checking accounts and payments in=
frastructure and tastefully decorated branches and bonus checks are all con=
sequences of it.

We have been talking about this a lot because it has broken down a bit: Peo=
ple have=C2=A0noticed=C2=A0that banks are risky, and so they have gotten mo=
re nervous about their risk-averse deposits. And the result is that banks =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0at least, US regional banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0are=C2=A0worse le=
nders; their funding model (leveraging a little bit of equity with a lot of=
 deposits that can be withdrawn at any time) is no longer a great match for=
 long-term loans. And so banks (at least, US regional banks) do seem to be =
retreating from lending, leading to the =E2=80=9Cde-banking of the world=E2=
=80=9D and an opportunity for private credit.
Where does that leave banks? One possible idea here is, like, =E2=80=9Cadd =
another layer of obfuscation.=E2=80=9D So the traditional form is:
=09Banks have some risk-taking equity.=09They leverage that with a whole lo=
t of risk-averse demand deposits.=09They use the money to make loans.

And we have talked about=C2=A0the alternative of =E2=80=9Cnarrow banking,=
=E2=80=9D which goes like this:
=09You deposit your money at the Fed or whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0it doesn=E2=
=80=99t go to loans.=09Separate lending companies raise equity investment f=
rom people who want to invest in loans.=09They use that equity funding to m=
ake loans.

And that is in fact a part of the story of private credit: Private-credit m=
anagers have longer-term and more risk-aware funding, from insurance compan=
ies,   retail investors in private-lending funds, etc. The rise of private =
credit is a move to=C2=A0   somewhat=C2=A0narrower banking, where more long=
-term lending is funded by long-term risk capital rather than by bank depos=
its.
But you could imagine a synthesis:
=09Banks have some equity and take a lot of deposits.=09Separate lending co=
mpanies raise equity from people who want to invest in loans.=09The banks=
=C2=A0lend money to the lending companies=C2=A0to leverage=C2=A0their=C2=A0=
equity.=09Now the bank loans are safer: They represent senior claims on sen=
ior claims; a bank=E2=80=99s=C2=A0depositors lose money only after (1) the =
lending company loses all its equity and (2) the bank loses all its equity.=
=09Also, the mystification of banking is a bit more mystifying: Instead of =
banks lending money to businesses, they lend money to people who lend money=
 to businesses; the path from risky investments to safe bank deposits is=C2=
=A0longer and more obscure.

And this too is part of the story of private credit. We   talked last month=
 about the fact that typical private credit funds don=E2=80=99t just use eq=
uity funding to make loans; they sometimes borrow money to leverage their c=
apital, and that borrowing is =E2=80=9Cmainly from U.S. financial instituti=
ons.=E2=80=9D And this week the Financial Times=E2=80=99=C2=A0Lex column no=
tes:

On Monday, PacWest Bancorp announced it had sold a $2.3bn portfolio of loan=
s=C2=A0to Ares Management for around 90 cents on the dollar in cash, part-f=
inanced by Barclays.
Ares manages $360bn which makes it one of the biggest private fund managers=
 in the world.=C2=A0PacWest had some $25bn of deposits as of early May and =
is one of the most beleaguered regional banks in the US.
Fleeing customers forced it to shore up liquidity by borrowing from Federal=
 Home Loan Bank and the Federal Reserve at rates far steeper than interest =
paid to depositors. Deposits will not return at scale unless PacWest offers=
 higher interest rates. The bank has therefore decided to retrench. That le=
aves fringe assets to the likes of Ares.
Ares is using leverage in the form of financing from Barclays to complete t=
he purchase of loans. Private asset managers have not made banks completely=
 obsolete, it appears. But their scale and the kinds of credit they origina=
te is changing. =E2=80=A6
Ares itself has various credit funds whose strategies demand returns betwee=
n 5 and 15 per cent. Some may call on modest leverage. Regardless of this, =
such borrowings bear the inherent extra costs of matching asset and liabili=
ty durations.
Banks like Barclays are best positioned to be lenders. They are large, heav=
ily regulated and prefer credit types that involve less underwriting than f=
unds like Ares. Like all good rebels, private capital managers are finding =
benefits from doing business with the establishment.

The old model was that US regional banks made complicated loans that requir=
ed a lot of underwriting, and funded them with bank deposits. That model lo=
oks risky now. The new model is something like:
=09US regional banks make complicated loans that require a lot of underwrit=
ing;=09They fund them with long-term money from private credit funds;=09The=
 private credit funds get long-term equity=C2=A0funding from their investor=
s and also senior funding from big multinational banks.=09The big multinati=
onal banks get their funding from deposits.

The deposits are still used to make loans, but in a safer and more indirect=
 way.

