 #ccc;">  retired in 2019</a>, lots of bond portfolios were actively manage=
d, there was big money and lots of competition in the bond-management busin=
ess, and Gross=E2=80=99s own recent performance wasn=E2=80=99t great.=C2=A0=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you were a hotshot innovator in the credit =
department of an insurance company in the 2020s, it might occur to you to d=
o the <em>opposite=C2=A0</em>of Gross. You might think thoughts like these:=
</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Look, I=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>sit on =
a pot of insurance money; I really=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>hold bonds to mat=
urity. I don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>need </em>instantaneous liquidity on my bon=
d investments. Given the choice between a liquid tradeable bond paying 6%, =
and an illiquid non-tradeable bond that I can=E2=80=99t sell for 10 years b=
ut that pays 6.5%, maybe I should take the higher interest rate and just wa=
it.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There is, in general, in=
 financial markets, an illiquidity premium: Bonds that can=E2=80=99t be tra=
ded tend to pay higher interest rates than=C2=A0 equally good bonds that ca=
n be traded. So I probably=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>get an extra 0.5% for buy=
ing hard-to-trade bonds.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When comp=
anies issue widely tradeable bonds, there is a lot of <em>process</em>. The=
y have to hire investment banks to find enough investors to buy the bonds; =
those banks charge fees for their efforts. If I just=C2=A0<em>went to compa=
nies I liked and asked to lend them money directly</em>, without involving =
a bank, we could cut out some middlemen and some fees; I would capture more=
 of the value because the banks would get less.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">If I pick my own borrowers and structure my own deals, =
I can probably get higher returns and higher credit quality than if I just =
buy whatever the big banks are bringing to market each week, and that might=
 be better for my performance than trying to actively trade bonds in a comp=
etitive market.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Simplistically, when no one has discovered the=
 idea of trading bonds, you can get better returns by trading bonds. When e=
veryone trades bonds, you can get better returns by not trading bonds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(As a technical point, if you were a hotshot i=
nnovator in the credit department of an insurance company in the 2020s,=C2=
=A0you probably wouldn=E2=80=99t work at an=C2=A0<em>insurance company</em>=
; you=E2=80=99d probably work at an alternative asset manager that happens =
to own, or run money for, an insurance company.)</p>
