<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Banks have some equity and take a lot=
 of deposits.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Separate lending com=
panies raise equity from people who want to invest in loans.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The banks=C2=A0<em>lend money to the lending com=
panies=C2=A0</em>to leverage=C2=A0<em>their=C2=A0</em>equity.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now the bank loans are safer: They represent se=
nior claims on senior claims; a bank=E2=80=99s=C2=A0depositors lose money o=
nly after (1) the lending company loses all its equity and (2) the bank los=
es all its equity.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Also, the mysti=
fication of banking is a bit more mystifying: Instead of banks lending mone=
y to businesses, they lend money to people who lend money to businesses; th=
e path from risky investments to safe bank deposits is=C2=A0longer and more=
 obscure.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And this too is part of the story of private c=
redit. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31919120=
.257399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDU=
tMDkvaXQtcy1uZXZlci10b28tbGF0ZS1mb3ItYmFua3MtdG8taGVkZ2U_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyNz=
IzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX=
3Rlcm09MjMwNjI3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCab=
7e6522" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">  talked last month</a> about the fact that typical private=
 credit funds don=E2=80=99t just use equity funding to make loans; they som=
etimes borrow money to leverage their capital, and that borrowing is =E2=80=
=9Cmainly from U.S. financial institutions.=E2=80=9D And this week the Fina=
ncial Times=E2=80=99=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/31919120.257399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMGM1NTM1YjItMjF=
iNi00YWE0LWJmMTctZDBkYmFmZjc3ZjBl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9917811c" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">Lex column notes</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Monday, PacWest Bancorp announced it had so=
ld a $2.3bn portfolio of loans=C2=A0to Ares Management for around 90 cents =
on the dollar in cash, part-financed by Barclays.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ares manages $360bn which makes it one of the =
biggest private fund managers in the world.=C2=A0PacWest had some $25bn of =
deposits as of early May and is one of the most beleaguered regional banks =
in the US.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fleeing customers forced it to shore up liquid=
ity by borrowing from Federal Home Loan Bank and the Federal Reserve at rat=
es far steeper than interest paid to depositors. Deposits will not return a=
t scale unless PacWest offers higher interest rates. The bank has therefore=
 decided to retrench. That leaves fringe assets to the likes of Ares.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ares is using leverage in the form of financin=
g from Barclays to complete the purchase of loans. Private asset managers h=
ave not made banks completely obsolete, it appears. But their scale and the=
 kinds of credit they originate is changing. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ares itself has various credit funds whose str=
ategies demand returns between 5 and 15 per cent. Some may call on modest l=
everage. Regardless of this, such borrowings bear the inherent extra costs =
of matching asset and liability durations.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Banks like Barclays are best positioned to be =
lenders. They are large, heavily regulated and prefer credit types that inv=
olve less underwriting than funds like Ares. Like all good rebels, private =
capital managers are finding benefits from doing business with the establis=
hment.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The old model was that US regional banks made =
complicated loans that required a lot of underwriting, and funded them with=
 bank deposits. That model looks risky now. The new model is something like=
:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">US regional banks make complicated lo=
ans that require a lot of underwriting;</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">They fund them with long-term money from private credit funds;</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The private credit funds get long-term=
 equity=C2=A0funding from their investors and also senior funding from big =
multinational banks.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The big multi=
national banks get their funding from deposits.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The deposits are still used to make loans, but=
 in a safer and more indirect way.</p>
